ana", "dst": "moksha", "rel": "grants", "src_name": "Siddhasana", "dst_name": "Moksha"}, {"src": "siddhasana", "dst": "bhrumadhyadrishti", "rel": "uses", "src_name": "Siddhasana", "dst_name": "Bhru-madhya Drishti"}, {"src": "padmasana", "dst": "nasagradrishti", "rel": "uses", "src_name": "Padmasana", "dst_name": "Nasagra Drishti"}, {"src": "bhadrasana", "dst": "jalandharabandha", "rel": "uses", "src_name": "Bhadrasana", "dst_name": "Jalandhara Bandha"}, {"src": "bhadrasana", "dst": "nasagradrishti", "rel": "uses", "src_name": "Bhadrasana", "dst_name": "Nasagra Drishti"}, {"src": "muktasana", "dst": "siddhi", "rel": "grants", "src_name": "Muktasana", "dst_name": "Siddhi"}, {"src": "vajrasana", "dst": "siddhi", "rel": "grants", "src_name": "Vajrasana", "dst_name": "Siddhi"}, {"src": "vajrasana", "dst": "yogi", "rel": "is_for", "src_name": "Vajrasana", "dst_name": "Yogi"}, {"src": "simhasana", "dst": "jalandharabandha", "rel": "uses", "src_name": "Simhasana", "dst_name": "Jalandhara Bandha"}, {"src": "simhasana", "dst": "nasagradrishti", "rel": "uses", "src_name": "Simhasana", "dst_name": "Nasagra Drishti"}, {"src": "shavasana", "dst": "yogi", "rel": "rests", "src_name": "Shavasana", "dst_name": "Yogi"}, {"src": "matsyendrasana", "dst": "bhrumadhyadrishti", "rel": "uses", "src_name": "Matsyendrasana", "dst_name": "Bhru-madhya Drishti"}, {"src": "gorakshasana", "dst": "jalandharabandha", "rel": "uses", "src_name": "Gorakshasana", "dst_name": "Jalandhara Bandha"}, {"src": "gorakshasana", "dst": "nasagradrishti", "rel": "uses", "src_name": "Gorakshasana", "dst_name": "Nasagra Drishti"}, {"src": "gorakshasana", "dst": "siddhi", "rel": "grants", "src_name": "Gorakshasana", "dst_name": "Siddhi"}, {"src": "paschimottanasana", "dst": "paschimottanasana", "rel": "alias_of", "src_name": "Paschimottanasana", "dst_name": "Paschimottanasana"}], "beats": [{"i": 0, "title": "The Potter's Wheel and the Unbaked Pot: Gheranda Teaches Canda Kapali", "summary": "The opening chapter of the Gheranda Samhita, framed as a dialogue: the seeker Canda Kapali approaches the sage Gheranda and asks to be taught Ghatastha Yoga (the yoga of the body-vessel) as the cause of knowledge of reality (tattvajnana). Gheranda praises the question and declares that there is no bondage like maya, no power greater than yoga, no friend higher than knowledge, and no enemy worse than ego. He explains that the jiva, like a potter's wheel turning by the force of past good and bad deeds (karma), revolves through birth and death; the body is an unbaked clay pot that must be fired in the flame of yoga to be purified. He then lays out the sevenfold discipline of Ghatastha Yoga — purification, firmness, steadiness, patience, lightness, direct perception, and non-attachment — mapped onto seven limbs (shatkarma, asana, mudra, pratyahara, pranayama, dhyana, samadhi) culminating in liberation. The chapter then begins the shatkarmas, detailing the four kinds of dhauti (cleansing), especially the fourfold antardhauti (vatasara air-cleansing, varisara water-cleansing, vahnisara fire/navel-cleansing, and bahishkrita), promising that mastery yields a \"divine body\" (devadeha) and freedom from disease — secret practices not to be revealed.", "cast": ["gheranda", "candakapali", "adishvara", "ghatasthayoga", "hathayogavidya", "rajayoga", "tattvajnana", "maya", "ahamkara", "karma", "jiva", "ghata"]}, {"i": 1, "title": "The Vessel Made Divine, Gherandas Secret Cleansings", "summary": "Gheranda Samhita GhS_1.22 to GhS_1.44 continue the shatkarma cleansings of ghatastha yoga. It completes the secret prakshalana of washing the abdominal shakti nadi navel deep in water, said unattainable even by the gods and to grant a divine body, devadeha. It gives Danta dhauti, cleansing teeth root, lengthening the lambika by milking with butter, cleansing the ear cavities to awaken nada, and pressing the frontal aperture so divine sight, divyadrishti, arises. It gives Hrd dhauti in three modes, Danda reed stick, Vamana water vomiting, Vasa cloth swallowing, against heart disease and kapha pitta. Finally Mula shodhana cleanses the root, easing apana and kindling the digestive fire, vahni mandala.", "cast": ["dhauti", "shaktinadicleansing", "dantadhauti", "lambikaelongation", "karnarandhracleansing", "bhalarandhracleansing", "hrddhauti", "dandadhauti", "vamanadhauti", "vasodhauti", "mulashodhana", "nadi"]}, {"i": 2, "title": "Gheranda Purifies the Vessel: From the Six Cleansings to the Seat of the Adept", "summary": "The closing portion of the Gheranda Samhita's first upadesha (instruction) on the shatkarma — the six purification practices of ghatastha-yoga (yoga of the body-vessel) — taught by sage Gheranda to his disciple Chanda(kapali). It completes the description of basti (yogic enema, in jala/water and shushka/dry forms, done in utkatasana with ashwini-mudra to draw and expel, curing constipation, indigestion, urinary disorders, gudavarta and disorders of krura-vayu), neti (threading a fine thread through the nostril and out the mouth, granting khechari-siddhi, divya-drishti/divine sight, and destroying kapha-dosha), lauliki/nauli (churning the belly rapidly side to side to destroy all disease and kindle the body's fire), trataka (steady unblinking gaze at a subtle point until tears flow, yielding the shambhavi state and divya-drishti), and kapalabhati in its three modes — vamakrama, vyutkrama, and shitkrama (breath and water drawn through ida/pingala and nostrils/mouth to destroy kapha-dosha, ward off old age and fever, and make the body free and luminous \"like Kamadeva\"). It closes the first upadesha (the colophon naming shatkarma-sadhana) and opens the second upadesha on asana: Shiva long ago declared 84 lakh asanas matching the 84 lakh species of living beings, of which 84 are distinguished, 32 are auspicious and siddhi-giving in the mortal world; these 32 are enumerated (siddha, padma, bhadra, mukta, vajra, svastika, simha, gomukha, vira, dhanura, mrita, gupta, matsya, matsyendra, goraksha, paschimottana, utkata, sankata, mayura, kukkuta, kurma, uttanakurmaka, uttanamanduka, vriksha, manduka, garuda, vrisha, shalabha, makara, ushtra, bhujanga, yoga). The fragment ends mid-description of siddhasana (pressing the perineum, gazing between the brows with restrained senses).", "cast": ["gheranda", "chanda", "shiva", "kamadeva", "gherandasamhita", "shatkarma", "basti", "neti", "lauliki", "trataka", "kapalabhati", "ashwinimudra"]}, {"i": 3, "title": "The Sage's Catalogue of Seats: From the Corpse to the Door of Liberation", "summary": "This section of the Gheranda Samhita (chapter 2 verses, GhS_2.7–2.27) is the asana (posture) catalogue of Gheranda's seven-limbed (saptanga) Hatha-Yoga, taught by sage Gheranda to king Chanda-Kapali. It defines a sequence of seated and reclining postures by exact anatomical construction and states the specific fruit of each: Siddhasana — heel pressed below the genitals, chin on the chest, gaze fixed between the eyebrows, declared the posture that 'breaks open the door-leaf of liberation' (mokshakapata-bhedana); Padmasana — feet crossed onto the opposite thighs, hands gripping the toes from behind, chin to chest, gaze on the nose-tip, destroyer of disease and disorder; Bhadrasana — soles joined below the perineum, hands holding the feet behind, with jalandhara (throat-lock) and nose-tip gaze, destroyer of all disease; Muktasana, Vajrasana, Svastikasana, Simhasana (with open mouth, throat-lock and nose-tip gaze, destroyer of all disease), Gomukhasana, Virasana, Dhanurasana (the body bent like a bow), Mritasana/Shavasana (the corpse pose that removes fatigue and rests the mind), Guptasana, Matsyasana (curing disease), Matsyendrasana, Gorakshasana (with throat-contraction and nose-tip gaze, granter of siddhi), Paschimottanasana / Yogendra-pitha, and Utkatasana. The passage repeatedly couples a precise physical lock (chin/throat/genital seat) with a fixed inward gaze and a named result — health, freedom from disorder, or attainment (siddhi).", "cast": ["gheranda", "gherandasamhita", "asana", "siddhasana", "padmasana", "bhadrasana", "muktasana", "vajrasana", "svastikasana", "simhasana", "gomukhasana", "virasana"]}]}